 spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]}]},{"name":"Barbe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Laurent, Andre, Gillis, Jean Pierre, Serge, Sylvie, Thierry, Yves.","French: descriptive nickname for someone with a beard, Old French <i>barbe</i> (from Latin <i>barba</i>).","French (<b>Barbé</b>): adjectival derivative of 1, meaning ‘bearded’."],"variants":[{"name":"Barb","meanings":["German: variant of   Barbe  . This surname is also found in France (mainly Alsace).","Romanian: variant of   Barbu  ."]},{"name":"Barbier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique, Emile, Pierre, Alexandre, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Laurette, Manon, Marcel, Marcellin, Michel.","French: occupational name for a barber-surgeon (see   Barber  ), Old French <i>barbier</i> (from Late Latin <i>barbarius</i>, a derivative of <i>barba</i> ‘beard’). Compare   Barbe   and   Barbee  .","German: occupational name for a barber, from Middle High German <i>barbierer</i>, or an occupational name for an armorer, from <i>barbier(e)</i> ‘metal visor (to protect the face)’."]},{"name":"Barbon","meanings":["English: habitational name from Barbon in Westmorland. The placename is probably from Old Norse <i>bjórr</i> ‘beaver’ + <i>brunnr</i> ‘stream’, alternatively from Old English <i>bera</i> ‘bear’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bare bon</i> ‘bare bone’, perhaps denoting a thin or bare-legged man.","French and English (of French Huguenot origin): nickname for a bearded man, from an augmentative of French   Barbe  ."]},{"name":"Barby","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Merwin, Otto, Wolfgang.  French Celestine, Pierre.","German: habitational name from a place so named in Saxony-Anhalt.","French (mainly Dordogne): derivative of   Barbe   1."]},{"name":"Barbin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Angelle, Marcel.","French: diminutive of   Barbe   1."]},{"name":"Barbot","meanings":["French:","from the Old French female personal name <i>Barbot</i>, a diminutive of   Barbe  , a short form of   Barbara  .","nickname for someone who tended to speak indistinctly, from French <i>barboter</i> ‘to babble’, or for someone with a beard, from a diminutive of Old French <i>barbe</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Barbay","meanings":["French: variant of <b>Barbé</b> (see   Barbe  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic 